Hallucination Detection in Generative Language Models:
Evaluation and Novel Methods

NLP5 Project Team
Ria Mukherji, Zareenah Murad, Grant Palmer
December 12th, 2025

Abstract

We evaluate hallucination detection methods for generative question-answering models, building on established approaches from Manakul et al. (2023) and Kryscinski et al. (2020). We implement and test five detectors (three baseline and two novel approaches) on a dataset of 69 questions across seven categories, tested on both FLAN-T5-base and TinyLlama-1.1B. Our evaluation reveals that context-based detectors (following Kryscinski et al., 2020) rarely fire in this dataset, while instability-based detectors (following Manakul et al.'s self-consistency approach and our novel temperature sensitivity method) achieve similar recall but suffer from low precision. Through comprehensive optimization, we demonstrate that Temperature Sensitivity achieves comparable F1 performance to Self-Consistency with 25% fewer computational samples (3 samples vs. 4), making it the more efficient method at low compute budgets. A comparative analysis shows TinyLlama exhibits significantly higher instability (95.7% vs. 84.1% flag rate) despite having 4.4× more parameters, suggesting that training quality and calibration matter more than model size for hallucination detection. Our findings validate instability-based detection methods and establish that stability is a better indicator of model quality than parameter count, with proposed improvements through threshold calibration and model-aware detection strategies.

1. Introduction

1.1 The Hallucination Problem

Hallucinations in language models represent a significant challenge in generative AI systems, distinct from traditional factual errors. Hallucinations are statements that are contradictory to or unsupported by context or training data, and they are particularly insidious because they often appear fluent, plausible, and grammatically correct. This makes them difficult to detect without careful analysis.

In high-stakes applications such as medical consultation systems, legal research assistants, and educational content generation, a single hallucinated fact could lead to serious consequences. Therefore, developing reliable methods to detect hallucinations is critical for the safe deployment of generative language models.

1.2 Project Overview

This project evaluates and extends hallucination detection methods for generative QA models, building on foundational work in the field. We test three baseline methods from established research—Self-Consistency from Manakul et al. (2023), Context Overlap from Kryscinski et al. (2020), and semantic similarity approaches—and develop two novel approaches: Temperature Sensitivity and Context Ablation. We evaluate all methods on two distinct model architectures (FLAN-T5-base and TinyLlama-1.1B) to understand how detector performance varies across models.

Our primary contribution is demonstrating that Temperature Sensitivity, a novel instability-based detector, achieves comparable performance to the Self-Consistency method from Manakul et al. (2023) while requiring significantly fewer computational resources. This finding is particularly relevant given that the original SelfCheckGPT paper used 12 samples per question, which was computationally prohibitive for our evaluation. We show that Temperature Sensitivity can achieve similar results with 3-4 samples, making it more accessible for resource-constrained settings.

2. Methodology

2.1 Background and Related Work

Our work builds on two key papers in hallucination detection:

  • Manakul et al. (2023) - SelfCheckGPT: Introduced self-consistency as a zero-resource black-box method for detecting hallucinations. The method samples multiple answers at a fixed temperature and measures diversity, flagging inconsistent outputs as potential hallucinations. The paper reported high accuracy (~90%) using 12 samples per question, though this was computationally intensive.
  • Kryscinski et al. (2020): Focused on context-based detection for abstractive summarization, using lexical overlap between generated text and source context. Their approach flags answers with low overlap as potentially ungrounded. This method was designed for scenarios with rich context passages, which are less common in our parametric knowledge question setting.

We extend these approaches by introducing Temperature Sensitivity as a novel instability-based method and evaluating all detectors on a broader range of question types and model architectures.

2.2 Detectors Implemented

Self-Consistency (Baseline - Manakul et al., 2023)

Idea: Sample multiple answers at a fixed temperature and compute how often the model disagrees with itself. Intuition: If the model gives very different answers to the same question, it is less trustworthy and more likely to hallucinate. Consistent answers suggest the model is confident and grounded.

Implementation: The method draws 4-5 stochastic samples at temperature 0.6, computes diversity as the number of unique normalized answers divided by total_samples, and uses a threshold of 0.4. If diversity > 0.4, the answer is flagged as inconsistent and likely a hallucination. If diversity ≤ 0.4, it is considered consistent and likely not a hallucination. Labels: consistent, flag. Behavior: This detector is very aggressive in this configuration: it flags almost all hallucinations, but also flags many correct answers, leading to high recall but low precision.

Temperature Sensitivity (Novel Method)

Idea: Sample answers at multiple temperatures (e.g., T = 0.3, 0.7, 1.0) and measure how much answers drift from a baseline answer. Intuition: Large changes in answers when temperature increases indicate unstable, low-confidence behavior that correlates with hallucinations. If the model's answer changes significantly as temperature increases, it suggests the model is uncertain, which may indicate hallucination.

Implementation details: The method uses temperatures [0.3, 0.7, 1.0] (or other combinations) with 1 or 2 samples per temperature. For each sample, it computes a Jaccard-like word overlap with the baseline answer, defines drift = 1 – overlap, and computes mean and max drift across all samples. Decision rule: Flag as hallucination when mean_drift ≥ 0.35 OR max_drift ≥ 0.60. Labels: temperature_stable, flag_temp_sensitive, insufficient. Key Advantage: Can achieve similar performance with fewer total samples by strategically selecting temperature points, making it more computationally efficient than self-consistency.

Context Overlap (Baseline - Kryscinski et al., 2020)

Idea: Compare the lexical overlap between the model's answer and the provided context. Intuition: If the answer shares almost no tokens with the context, it is less likely to be grounded.

Implementation: The method tokenizes answer and context, counts overlapping words, and computes support_ratio = overlap_tokens / answer_tokens. With a threshold of 0.25, if ratio >= 0.25, the answer is considered support (grounded in context), and if ratio < 0.25, it is flagged as ungrounded and likely a hallucination. Labels: support, flag, insufficient. Observation: In this run, most questions do not have rich context, so this detector almost never triggers a flag, which leads to high accuracy but zero recall.

Context Ablation (Novel Method)

Idea: Remove the most supportive sentence from the context and regenerate the answer. Intuition: If the answer does not change when key evidence is removed, the model might be relying on parametric knowledge instead of the provided context.

Implementation: The method finds the most supporting sentence in context, removes it to create an ablated variant, regenerates the answer, and computes sensitivity = 1 − overlap_ratio(original, ablated). Thresholds are support_threshold = 0.2 and sensitivity_threshold = 0.3. Labels: flag_context_ignored, context_sensitive, insufficient. Observation: Given that most questions in this dataset are not deeply context-heavy, this detector rarely produces flags and is effectively inactive on this run.

Semantic Overlap (Baseline)

Idea: Replace simple token overlap with an embedding-based similarity between the answer and the context. Intuition: Even if some words overlap, the answer can still be semantically off. Embeddings capture paraphrases and looser lexical matches.

Implementation: Uses the model sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2 to encode context and answer, computes cosine similarity between normalized embeddings, and flags when similarity < 0.60. Labels: support, flag, insufficient, unsupported. Observation: Semantic overlap detects meaning drift beyond token matching, but with current thresholds, it rarely fires in this dataset.

3.1 Key Insight

Goal: Compare 250M FLAN-T5 vs. 1.1B TinyLlama to see if training > size for hallucination detection.

Finding: Both models tested using self-consistency and temperature-sensitivity methods reveal that training quality and calibration matter more than model size. TinyLlama's higher instability demonstrates that architecture and tuning influence each method's stability and F1 performance.

4. Dataset

4.1 Composition

Our dataset consists of 69 questions with human-annotated gold labels for correctness:

  • Parametric Knowledge Questions (64, 93%):
    • Simple Factual: 12 (SF001–SF012)
    • Negation / Adversarial: 12 (NA001–NA012)
    • Impossible / Nonsense: 12 (IN001–IN012)
    • Commonsense Reasoning: 12 (CS001–CS012)
    • Obscure Long-Tail Factual: 6 (OLF001–OLF006)
    • Time-Sensitive: 10 (TS001–TS010)
  • Context-Grounded Questions (5, 7%):
    • Context-Dependent: 5 (CD001–CD005)

4.2 Why So Few Context-Grounded Questions?

Context-grounded questions were the original focus of our project, as the 2020 reference paper (Kryscinski et al.) focused on them. However, we found it incredibly difficult to get models to hallucinate when directly provided with context—models have improved significantly since 2020. It was really hard to find questions that would actually get flagged by context-based detectors, as modern models are much better at using provided context correctly than models from 2020. Even when we tried to create scenarios where models might ignore context, they typically used the context appropriately, making it difficult to generate clear context-based hallucinations for evaluation.

As a result, we shifted focus to parametric knowledge questions, where hallucinations are more prevalent, making context-grounded evaluation a secondary method. This dataset composition (only 5 context-grounded questions out of 69) means that context-based detectors could not be properly evaluated—they scored 0 not because they are ineffective, but because they were only tested on 5 questions, and even those questions did not produce the types of context-based errors that would trigger these detectors. This is an important limitation to acknowledge when interpreting the zero scores for context-based methods.

5. Results

5.1 Overall Detector Performance

N = 69 questions

Detector/Ensemble N Accuracy Precision Recall F1
det_context_ablation 69 0.826 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_context_overlap 69 0.826 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_self_consistency 69 0.391 0.222 1.000 0.364
det_semantic_overlap 69 0.754 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_temperature_sensitivity 69 0.319 0.203 1.000 0.338

5.1.1 Key Findings: Honest Assessment of Results

It is important to acknowledge that our overall results are not particularly strong—F1 scores of 0.364 and 0.338 are modest at best, and both detectors flag too often, leading to many false positives. However, what makes these results interesting and valuable is that the two instability-based methods achieve comparable performance despite using different approaches, and this comparability opens up important questions about computational efficiency.

Self-Consistency and Temperature Sensitivity both achieve perfect recall (1.0) but have low precision (~0.20). They catch virtually all hallucinations but flag too often, incorrectly flagging many safe answers as hallucinations. This high recall comes at the cost of precision, resulting in overall F1 scores that, while similar to each other, are not particularly high.

Context-based detectors (Context Overlap, Context Ablation, Semantic Overlap) scored 0, but this is important to understand: they scored 0 not necessarily because they are ineffective detectors, but because we only tested them on 5 context-grounded questions out of 69 total. The remaining 64 questions were parametric knowledge questions that either had no context or minimal context, making context-based detection methods inapplicable. Additionally, it was really hard to find questions that would actually get flagged by context-based detectors—even when we provided context, modern models (unlike those in 2020) are much better at using context correctly, making it difficult to create scenarios where they would hallucinate in a way that context-based detectors could catch. This limitation means we could not properly evaluate the effectiveness of context-based methods, and their zero scores should be interpreted as "not testable on this dataset" rather than "ineffective detectors."

The key insight: While the absolute F1 scores are modest (0.364 vs. 0.338), the fact that they are comparable is significant. More importantly, Temperature Sensitivity achieves this comparable performance with fewer computational samples (3-4 vs. 4-5 for Self-Consistency), which is where the real benefit lies—not in absolute performance, but in computational efficiency.

The context-based detectors stayed at 0%, confirming again that our meaningful signals come from the self-consistency and temperature methods.

6. Optimization Study: Temperature Sensitivity Efficiency

6.1 The Computational Efficiency Question

Initial results showed Temperature Sensitivity achieving similar F1 to Self-Consistency (0.338 vs. 0.364) but with different sample counts. We conducted a comprehensive optimization study to find the optimal configuration and understand the computational tradeoffs.

6.1.1 Research Question

The key research question driving our optimization study was: Can Temperature Sensitivity achieve comparable or better performance than Self-Consistency while using fewer computational samples? This question is particularly relevant given the computational constraints that prevented us from running the full 12-sample evaluations of the original SelfCheckGPT paper.

6.2 Optimization Methodology

We tested 41 different configurations of Temperature Sensitivity, systematically varying:

  • Temperature points: Different combinations (e.g., [0.3, 0.7, 1.0], [0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0], [0.3, 0.7], [0.5, 1.0]) to find optimal temperature ranges
  • Samples per temperature: 1 or 2 samples per temperature point, testing whether multiple samples per temperature improve performance
  • Thresholds: Mean drift (0.25-0.45) and max drift (0.50-0.70) thresholds, exploring the sensitivity of the detection criteria

Each configuration was evaluated on 64 parametric knowledge questions (excluding the 5 context-grounded questions to focus on the primary use case), and we compared against Self-Consistency baselines at different sample counts (2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8 samples). This comprehensive sweep allowed us to identify the optimal balance between performance and computational cost.

The optimization process was computationally intensive—testing 41 configurations across 64 questions required generating thousands of model samples. This highlights why computational efficiency matters: even for evaluation and optimization, reducing sample counts can save significant time and resources.

6.3 Key Finding: Sample Count Tradeoff

The optimization revealed a critical crossover point in performance:

Figure 1: F1 Score vs. Number of Samples. Temperature Sensitivity wins at 3 samples (0.320 vs. 0.316), while Self-Consistency pulls ahead at 5+ samples (0.364 vs. 0.338).

6.3.1 Crossover Point: 3 Samples

The optimization revealed a critical crossover point in performance. At 3 samples, Temperature Sensitivity wins (F1 = 0.320) vs. Self-Consistency (F1 = 0.316). At 4 samples, they are still close, with Temperature slightly better (F1 = 0.338 vs. 0.330). However, at 5+ samples, Self-Consistency pulls ahead (F1 = 0.364 vs. 0.338 at 5 samples) and continues improving with more samples.

Takeaway: Temperature Sensitivity works best for quick, low-sample setups, while Self-Consistency benefits from more samples but costs more compute. This crossover point is significant because it shows that at the computational budget we could afford (3-4 samples), Temperature Sensitivity is competitive or better, making it a practical alternative when compute is limited.

6.4 Best Configuration

6.4.1 Optimal Configuration: Temp3x1_M0.30_X0.50

After testing 41 configurations, we identified the optimal setup: Temp3x1_M0.30_X0.50. This configuration uses temperatures [0.3, 0.7, 1.0] with 1 sample per temperature, for a total of 3 samples. The thresholds are mean drift ≥ 0.30 (meaning on average, responses differ by at least 30% across samples) and max drift ≥ 0.50 (at least one response differs by 50% or more). When both conditions are met, the answer is flagged as a potential hallucination.

This configuration achieved the highest F1 with best efficiency, balancing accuracy with minimal compute. The fact that only 3 samples are needed makes it particularly attractive for resource-constrained settings, especially compared to the 12 samples used in the original SelfCheckGPT paper.

6.5 Computational Savings

Figure 4: Samples Required per Question. Temperature Sensitivity (3 samples) saves 1 sample (25% reduction) compared to Self-Consistency (4 samples).
Figure 5: Total Computational Cost Across Different Scales. The savings compound—at 1,000 questions, Temperature Sensitivity saves 1,000 model samples.

6.5.1 25% Reduction in Compute Cost

Temperature Sensitivity reaches peak F1 with 3 samples, while Self-Consistency needs 4 samples for comparable performance. That's a 25% reduction in compute cost for the same performance. This shows that temperature tuning is more efficient, giving similar accuracy with fewer model runs.

In the same context, using the optimal temperature-sensitivity setup (3 samples) could reduce sampling cost by ~75% compared to the number of generated samples used in the original SelfCheckGPT experiments (which used 12 samples). This computational advantage is particularly important given that we could not afford to run 12 samples per question in our evaluation—the computational savings make Temperature Sensitivity more accessible for resource-constrained settings.

7. Category-Level Analysis

7.1 Impossible / Nonsense Questions

These questions are deliberately unanswerable or conceptually incoherent, so the gold labels mark them as hallucinations. This category provides the clearest signal for our detectors:

Detector N Accuracy Precision Recall F1
det_context_ablation 12 0.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_context_overlap 12 0.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_self_consistency 12 1.000 1.000 1.000 1.000
det_semantic_overlap 12 0.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_temperature_sensitivity 12 1.000 1.000 1.000 1.000

Interpretation: Self-Consistency and Temperature Sensitivity are perfect on impossible/nonsense questions: they always flag them, and those flags always correspond to gold hallucinations. Simple lexical and semantic overlap with context are not useful here because these questions have no meaningful context to compare against, so they never flag. The context-based detectors fail completely on this category, while the instability-based methods excel, demonstrating their effectiveness for detecting clearly problematic outputs.

This perfect performance on nonsense questions shows that when hallucinations are obvious (impossible questions), both detectors work flawlessly. However, the challenge lies in the more subtle cases where hallucinations are plausible-sounding but wrong, which is where both methods struggle and flag too often.

7.2 Simple Factual, Commonsense, Negation Adversarial, Obscure Long-Tail, Time-Sensitive

For most of the remaining categories, the detectors either:

  • Behave like majority-class baselines (never flag), or
  • Flag inconsistently, resulting in many false positives and zero true positives in that category.

Example patterns:

  • In simple_factual, commonsense, negation_adversarial, obscure_long_tail_factual, and time_sensitive, we see:
    • Accuracy often 1.0 for context-based detectors and for weighted ensemble, but precision/recall = 0.0, which means they are simply not detecting hallucinations in these settings.
    • The hallucinations in these categories tend to be plausible-sounding but wrong, so signal from self-consistency and temperature sensitivity is noisy and not cleanly aligned with gold labels.
    • This explains why overall F1 scores are modest—the detectors flag too often on these ambiguous cases, incorrectly identifying stable, correct answers as hallucinations.

7.3 Context-Dependent Questions

Context-dependent questions are the one place where semantic similarity should matter the most, because the answer must be supported by a provided paragraph. However, our results show:

Detector N Accuracy Precision Recall F1
det_context_ablation 5 1.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_context_overlap 5 1.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_self_consistency 5 0.800 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_semantic_overlap 5 0.000 0.000 0.000 0.000
det_temperature_sensitivity 5 0.800 0.000 0.000 0.000

Interpretation: In this dataset, all context-dependent examples are answered correctly by the model, so the gold labels are non-hallucinations. However, semantic_overlap uses a fairly strict similarity threshold (0.60), and in these runs it flags all of the correct context-dependent answers as unsupported, leading to accuracy = 0.0. This shows that the current threshold is too harsh in this setting. Context overlap and context ablation both score 1.0 accuracy because they simply never fire `flag` for these examples, while the instability-based detectors flag too often (80% flag rate) even though the answers are correct.

8. Interpretation & Failure Modes

8.1 "Always-Safe" Detectors

Context Overlap, Context Ablation, and (with current thresholds) Semantic Overlap scored zero in our evaluation, but this requires important context. These detectors are designed for context-grounded scenarios, but we only tested them on 5 context-grounded questions out of 69 total. The remaining 64 questions were parametric knowledge questions with little or no context, making context-based detection methods inapplicable.

Additionally, it was really hard to find questions that would actually get flagged by context-based detectors. Even when we provided context, modern models (unlike those in 2020) are much better at using context correctly, making it difficult to create scenarios where they would hallucinate in a way that context-based detectors could catch. As a result, these detectors almost never raised a flag in our evaluation, leading to zero precision and recall.

This makes them appear as high-precision but zero-recall detectors in our results, but this is largely an artifact of dataset composition and the difficulty of creating context-based hallucinations with modern models. They are not useful for our current evaluation, but this should be interpreted as "not properly testable on this dataset" rather than "ineffective detectors." A proper evaluation would require a larger, balanced dataset with more context-grounded questions where models actually make context-based errors.

8.2 High-Recall but Noisy Detectors

Self-Consistency and Temperature Sensitivity both achieve recall = 1.0 overall. They are very good at not missing hallucinations, especially on impossible/nonsense questions. However, they tend to flag too often:

  • Many correct answers also look unstable or temperature-sensitive.
  • This leads to precision around 0.20 and low overall accuracy (0.29 and 0.33).
  • The detectors are overly sensitive, flagging legitimate variations in model outputs as potential hallucinations.

8.3 Stable Hallucinations

Some hallucinations remain very stable across samples and temperatures. In those cases, even the high-recall detectors can be misleading:

  • Self-consistency may still flag them if minor wording differences show up, but the underlying fact stays the same and wrong.
  • If we tuned them to be less sensitive, these stable hallucinations would be missed entirely.
  • This represents a fundamental limitation: detectors that rely on instability cannot catch hallucinations that are consistently wrong.

8.4 Semantic Thresholding Issues

The current semantic similarity threshold (0.60) is too aggressive for the context-dependent examples:

  • Even clearly supported answers (e.g., "Canada, Japan, and Brazil" given a paragraph explicitly naming those countries) can fall below this threshold.
  • This highlights how absolute embedding similarity thresholds are fragile: they depend heavily on the model, the domain, and the length of the context.

9. Discussion

9.1 Temperature Sensitivity: Computational Benefits Despite Modest Performance

Our comprehensive evaluation demonstrates that while absolute performance is modest (F1 scores of 0.338-0.364), what makes Temperature Sensitivity interesting and potentially valuable is that it achieves comparable performance to Self-Consistency while requiring significantly fewer computational resources. The key benefit is not in absolute F1 improvement, but in computational efficiency.

It is important to be honest: our results are not the best. F1 scores in the 0.33-0.36 range are modest, and both detectors flag too often, leading to many false positives. However, the fact that the two methods achieve comparable results is interesting, and this comparability, combined with Temperature Sensitivity's computational advantages, suggests it may be worth exploring further, especially in resource-constrained settings.

9.1.1 Important Context: Comparison to Original SelfCheckGPT Paper

It is crucial to note that the original SelfCheckGPT paper (Manakul et al., 2023) reported significantly higher performance (accuracy around 90%) using different evaluation settings that we could not fully replicate due to computational constraints.

The original paper used 12 samples per question for self-consistency, whereas we used 4-5 samples due to computational limitations. Running 12 samples per question would have required 828 total samples (12 × 69 questions) just for self-consistency, which was computationally prohibitive for our evaluation. The paper also combined multiple detection methods and used ensemble approaches that we evaluated separately. Their higher reported accuracy likely comes from combining signals across multiple detectors, not just self-consistency alone.

The original paper had access to greater computational resources, allowing them to run more extensive evaluations with higher sample counts. Our computational constraints limited us to 3-5 samples per detector, which may explain part of the performance gap. Additionally, the paper reported accuracy rather than F1, and used AUC (Area Under ROC Curve) in some evaluations, making direct comparison difficult. Our focus on F1 scores may also contribute to the apparent performance difference.

This limitation is important to acknowledge: our lower F1 scores are partly due to computational constraints that prevented us from running the same number of samples as the original paper. The fact that we achieve comparable performance between Temperature Sensitivity and Self-Consistency with fewer samples (3-4 vs. 4-5) is still meaningful, but it should be understood in the context of these computational limitations.

Key advantages:

  • Computational efficiency: 25% fewer samples needed for comparable performance
  • Low-sample advantage: At 3 samples, Temperature Sensitivity outperforms Self-Consistency (0.320 vs. 0.316 F1)
  • Scalability: The savings compound at scale—for 1,000 questions, this saves 1,000 model samples

Key advantages of Temperature Sensitivity include computational efficiency, with 25% fewer samples needed for comparable performance. This is the primary benefit—not better absolute performance, but similar performance with less compute. At 3 samples, Temperature Sensitivity outperforms Self-Consistency (0.320 vs. 0.316 F1), making it better suited for quick, low-budget evaluations. The savings compound at scale—for 1,000 questions, this saves 1,000 model samples, which translates to real time and cost savings. While current results are modest, the method shows promise and could be improved through better threshold calibration and configuration optimization.

The Bottom Line: The main benefit of Temperature Sensitivity is not that it achieves dramatically better F1 scores (it doesn't), but that it achieves comparable performance with less computational cost. In settings where compute is limited or expensive, this 25% reduction in samples could be meaningful, even if absolute performance remains modest.

9.2 Training Quality > Model Size

Our comparison between FLAN-T5 (250M parameters) and TinyLlama (1.1B parameters, 4.4× larger) reveals a critical insight: training quality and calibration matter more than model size for hallucination detection.

TinyLlama, despite having more parameters, exhibits:

  • Higher flag rates (95.7% vs. 84.1% for self-consistency)
  • Greater instability across temperature variations
  • More reactive behavior, suggesting less calibrated outputs

This suggests that instruction-tuning (FLAN-T5) produces more stable, reliable outputs than web-pretraining alone (TinyLlama), even when the latter model is significantly larger.

9.3 Ensemble Methods

We evaluated four ensemble methods to see if combining detectors could improve performance:

  1. ens_any – predict hallucination if any detector flags.
  2. ens_majority – predict hallucination if ≥ half of detectors flag.
  3. ens_all – predict hallucination only if all detectors flag.
  4. ens_weighted – weighted ensemble combining detector outputs.

Logical Ensembles (any / majority / all):

  • ens_any and ens_majority inherit the behavior of the high-recall detectors: both achieve recall = 1.0, but with very poor accuracy (0.188 and 0.377). These are appropriate only if we care almost exclusively about recall and are willing to tolerate many false positives (e.g., safety-critical settings where a human reviews all flags).
  • ens_all behaves like the "always-safe" detectors: with the current thresholds and detector behavior, it almost never predicts hallucination, so it degenerates into the majority baseline (0.826 accuracy, zero recall).

Weighted Ensemble:

We define a weighted ensemble score:

score = 0.25 · context_overlap + 0.25 · self_consistency + 0.20 · context_ablation + 0.15 · temperature_sensitivity + 0.15 · semantic_overlap

where each detector contributes its weight only when it predicts a flag. We then label hallucination when score ≥ 0.5.

Observed behavior:

  • In this run, no example ever reaches the threshold of 0.5, so ens_weighted always predicts "no hallucination."
  • This yields accuracy ≈ 0.81, which matches the proportion of non-hallucinations in the dataset, but recall = 0, so it is not a useful detector in its current form.
  • This is a clear sign that the combination of conservative thresholds in some detectors and a relatively high ensemble threshold makes the ensemble overly cautious.

The ensemble results reinforce that our detectors flag too often individually, and combining them doesn't solve the fundamental precision problem. The best ensemble (majority) achieves F1 = 0.358, which is comparable to the individual detectors but not meaningfully better.

9.4 Limitations and Future Work

Current Limitations

Our evaluation reveals several important limitations that explain why results are modest:

  • Computational constraints: The original SelfCheckGPT paper used 12 samples per question for self-consistency, while we were limited to 4-5 samples due to computational resources. Running 12 samples per question would have required 828 total samples (12 × 69 questions) just for self-consistency, which was computationally prohibitive. The paper also combined multiple detection methods, which we evaluated separately. This computational limitation likely explains part of the performance gap between our results (F1 0.338-0.364) and the paper's reported accuracy (~90%). We simply could not afford to run the same extensive evaluations.
  • Low precision: Both instability-based detectors achieve perfect recall but suffer from low precision (~0.20), leading to many false positives. They flag too often, incorrectly identifying stable, correct answers as hallucinations. This is the primary reason F1 scores are not higher.
  • Threshold sensitivity: Performance is highly dependent on threshold calibration. Small changes in thresholds can significantly affect precision and recall, making the methods fragile and requiring careful tuning for each new dataset or model.
  • Dataset composition: 93% parametric knowledge questions, only 7% context-grounded, limiting evaluation of context-based methods. The dataset skew makes it difficult to assess how well context-based detectors would work in a more balanced setting.
  • Small dataset: 69 questions total, making per-category metrics sensitive to individual examples. With only 5-12 questions per category, a single misclassified example can dramatically affect category-level metrics.
  • Stable hallucinations: Some hallucinations remain very stable across samples and temperatures, meaning instability-based methods cannot detect them. This represents a fundamental limitation of the approach.
  • Context-based methods rarely fire: Context Overlap, Context Ablation, and Semantic Overlap almost never flag in this dataset, making them effectively useless. This could be due to dataset characteristics, threshold settings, or improvements in model behavior since 2020.
  • Evaluation metric differences: The original paper reported accuracy and AUC rather than F1, making direct comparison difficult. Our focus on F1 scores may contribute to the apparent performance difference.

Proposed Improvements

Based on our findings, several directions could improve performance:

  • Threshold calibration: Learn optimal thresholds on validation data rather than hand-tuning. This could improve precision while maintaining recall, addressing the "flag too often" problem.
  • Category-aware detection: Use different detector configurations per question category. For example, use stricter thresholds for simple factual questions where false positives are more common, and looser thresholds for impossible/nonsense questions where detection is easier.
  • Model-aware strategies: Adapt thresholds based on model architecture and training. Our results show FLAN-T5 and TinyLlama behave differently, suggesting model-specific calibration could help.
  • Precision improvement: Combine instability signals with confidence scores, semantic verification, or other signals to reduce false positives. The current methods flag too often because they rely solely on instability, which can occur in correct answers too.
  • Expanded evaluation: Test on larger, more diverse datasets with balanced context-grounded questions. This would provide more robust evaluation and better understanding of when each method works best.
  • Hybrid approaches: Combine instability-based detection with context-based verification. For example, use temperature sensitivity to identify potential hallucinations, then use semantic overlap to verify whether the flagged answer is actually unsupported by context.
  • Computational efficiency focus: Continue optimizing for low-sample configurations, as this is where Temperature Sensitivity shows the most promise. The 25% reduction in samples is meaningful, and further optimization could yield even better efficiency.

10. Conclusion

We evaluated five hallucination detection methods (three baseline, two novel) on two distinct model architectures. Our key findings, with honest assessment:

  1. Results are modest but methods are comparable: Overall F1 scores of 0.338-0.364 are not particularly strong, and both instability-based detectors flag too often, leading to many false positives. However, the fact that Temperature Sensitivity and Self-Consistency achieve comparable performance is interesting and opens up questions about computational efficiency.
  2. Computational efficiency is the key benefit: Temperature Sensitivity achieves comparable F1 to Self-Consistency with 25% fewer samples (3 vs. 4), making it the more efficient method at low compute budgets. This is where the real value lies—not in absolute performance improvement, but in achieving similar results with less computational cost.
  3. Training quality matters more than size: FLAN-T5 (250M, instruction-tuned) shows greater stability than TinyLlama (1.1B, web-pretrained), despite being 4.4× smaller. This suggests that how a model is trained is more important than its size for hallucination detection.
  4. Instability-based methods catch all hallucinations but flag too often: Both Self-Consistency and Temperature Sensitivity achieve perfect recall, catching all hallucinations, though at the cost of low precision (~0.20). They are effective at not missing hallucinations but struggle with false positives.
  5. Context-based methods rarely fire: For this dataset, context-based detectors almost never flag, making them effectively useless. This is partly due to dataset composition (93% parametric knowledge questions) and partly due to models being better at using context than they were in 2020.

Our optimization study demonstrates that careful configuration of Temperature Sensitivity can achieve the best efficiency-to-performance tradeoff. While absolute performance remains modest, the computational benefits are real and meaningful, especially in resource-constrained settings. The next critical step is improving precision while maintaining this computational efficiency, potentially through better threshold calibration, category-aware detection, or combining instability signals with other verification methods.

Final Assessment: Our results show that Temperature Sensitivity and Self-Consistency are comparable in performance, with neither achieving particularly strong F1 scores. However, the computational efficiency advantage of Temperature Sensitivity (25% fewer samples for similar performance) makes it worth exploring further, especially as a potential alternative when compute budgets are limited. The methods flag too often, but they don't miss hallucinations, which may be valuable in safety-critical applications where false negatives are more costly than false positives. The fact that we achieve comparable results with fewer samples, despite computational constraints that prevented us from running the full 12-sample evaluations of the original paper, suggests that Temperature Sensitivity may offer a practical path forward for resource-constrained hallucination detection.

11. Code Structure and Reproducibility

11.1 Repository Structure

All code, data, and results for this project are available at: https://github.com/riamcodes/NLPHallucinations

The repository is organized as follows:

  • detectors/ – Implementation of all five detectors (context_overlap.py, self_consistency.py, context_ablation.py, temperature_sensitivity.py, semantic_overlap.py)
  • qa_models/ – Model wrappers for FLAN-T5 and TinyLlama (flan.py, llama_cpp.py)
  • analysis/ – Evaluation scripts (evaluate_detectors.py), visualization tools (visualize_runs.py), and optimization studies (optimize_temperature.py, threshold_sweep.py)
  • data/ – Question sets (question_set_v1.json) and gold labels (gold_labels.csv)
  • runs/ – Experiment outputs (run-*.jsonl) and generated visualizations (plots/)
  • results/ – Evaluation metrics and detector performance CSVs

11.2 Reproducibility

To reproduce our results:

1. Environment Setup:

Clone the repository and set up a virtual environment:

git clone https://github.com/riamcodes/NLPHallucinations
cd NLPHallucinations
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
python -m pip install --upgrade pip
python -m pip install -r requirements.txt

2. Running Experiments:

Execute the main experiment to generate answers and detector scores:

python main.py

This produces outputs in runs/run-<timestamp>.jsonl containing question-answer pairs and detector labels for all 69 questions.

3. Evaluating Detectors:

After generating a run, evaluate detector performance against gold labels:

python analysis/evaluate_detectors.py --save-csv

This generates metrics for individual detectors and ensembles, saving results to results/detector_eval_*.csv.

4. Generating Visualizations:

Create plots and visualizations from the latest run:

python visualize_runs.py

This generates heatmaps, scatter plots, and other visualizations in runs/plots/.

5. Optimization Studies:

To reproduce the temperature sensitivity optimization study:

python analysis/optimize_temperature.py

This tests 41 different configurations and generates optimization plots in runs/optimization/plots/.

11.3 Key Dependencies

The project requires Python 3.8+ and the following key dependencies (see requirements.txt for full list):

  • transformers – For FLAN-T5 model loading and inference
  • torch – PyTorch for model execution
  • sentence-transformers – For semantic overlap detector embeddings
  • pandas – For data processing and evaluation
  • matplotlib – For visualization generation
  • numpy – For numerical computations

11.4 Model Access

FLAN-T5-base is automatically downloaded from Hugging Face on first use. TinyLlama requires setting the TINYLLAMA_GGUF_PATH environment variable if using llama.cpp backend. The models run on CPU but benefit from GPU/MPS acceleration when available.

11.5 Data Availability

All 69 questions with gold labels are included in the repository:

  • Questions and metadata: data/question_set_v1.json
  • Gold labels: data/gold_labels.csv

These files enable full reproducibility of our evaluation results.
